<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-998-424  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 998 424.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lan Times  Dec 1989 v6 n12 p82(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Wasted brilliance: worm author could have done better.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Baker, Virginia.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Alleged Internet worm creator Robert T. Morris is regarded as acomputer hacking genius by some, but a realistic assessment of theInternet worm reveals a less impressive accomplishment.andP;  The codemanages to take advantage of two specific system flaws, finger andsendmail, but is not technically impressive.andP;  There were, in fact,many bugs and flaws in the program which, though sophisticated,could have been authored by any number of graduate orundergraduate students.andP;  The most obvious error perpetrated by theauthor of the worm is in the code's provision forself-replication.andP;  It betrays a lack of understanding ofpropagation and load functions.andP;  If anything, Morris displaysnaivete in assuming he could launch an unsimulated complex wormonto a complex network and have it function correctly the firsttime.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Internet (Computer network)Computer VirusesData SecurityComputer Hackers.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>